{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470927"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"81"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471190"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"81"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"81","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/81"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.34,0.12,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"81"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101640"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"81","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/81"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"81"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4923"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101640"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with fever and poor feeding over the past 10 hours. His mother reports he has deteriorated quickly after being completely well yesterday. He has no significant medical history, was born at term with normal birth weight, and his immunisations are up to date. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 136/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 44/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.8\u00b0C. He responds sluggishly to voice and appears irritable. His peripheries are warm with capillary refill time of one second. His anterior fontanelle is full but not bulging. There is no rash or focal neurological signs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nasopharyngeal aspiration","Complete blood examination","Blood culture","Urine microscopy and culture","Lumbar puncture"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with features concerning for bacterial meningitis including fever, irritability, lethargy and a full fontanelle. While several investigations are important in the work-up, \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important diagnostic test as it provides definitive evidence of meningitis and identifies the causative organism to guide specific therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete blood examination\u003C/strong\u003E may show elevated white cell count and inflammatory markers suggestive of infection, but these findings are non-specific and do not confirm the diagnosis of meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are essential to identify bacteraemia but may be negative in up to 15-20% of cases of bacterial meningitis. They should be collected but are not the most important diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E is important in the febrile infant to exclude urinary tract infection, but the clinical features in this case are more suggestive of meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasopharyngeal aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E may identify viral pathogens but would not assist in diagnosing or excluding bacterial meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is crucial to note that while lumbar puncture is the most important diagnostic test, empiric antibiotics should not be delayed while awaiting the procedure. In an unwell infant with suspected meningitis, broad-spectrum antibiotics should be administered within 30 minutes of the decision to treat, with dexamethasone given just before or with the first dose of antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In infants with suspected meningitis, lumbar puncture is the key diagnostic investigation but should not delay antibiotic administration.","Typical signs of meningitis in infants include fever, irritability, lethargy and a full fontanelle.","Empiric antibiotics should be given within 30 minutes of the decision to treat suspected meningitis."],"references":["Meningitis and encephalitis. In: Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Meningitis_Guideline/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"81"}},"stemMedia":{